All Life Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

Background:¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective: To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Key Questions:¶

  1. How many different segments of customers are there?
  2. How are these segments different from each other?
  3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Data Description:¶

Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

Steps to follow:¶

1. Perform univariate analysis on the data to better understand the variables at your disposal and to get an idea about the no of clusters. Perform EDA, create visualizations to explore data. (10 marks)

def df_col_analysis(df, fieldName):
    maxVal= df[fieldName].max()
    minVal=df[fieldName].min()
    Q1=df[fieldName].quantile(q=0.25)
    Q3=df[fieldName].quantile(q=0.75)
    L_outliers=Q1-1.5*(Q3-Q1)
    U_outliers=Q3+1.5*(Q3-Q1)
    print('==========='+ fieldName.upper())
    print('Column Name : '+ fieldName)
    print('Range : ', minVal, ' to ', maxVal)
    print('Mean : ', df[fieldName].mean())
    print('Median : ', df[fieldName].median())
    print('Std Dev : ', df[fieldName].std())
    print('Lower outliers : ', L_outliers)
    print('Upper outliers : ', U_outliers)
    print('Number of outliers in  upper : ', df[df[fieldName]>U_outliers][fieldName].count())
    print('Number of outliers in  lower : ', df[df[fieldName]<L_outliers][fieldName].count())
    print('% of Outlier in  upper: ',round(df[df[fieldName]>U_outliers][fieldName].count()*100/len(df)), '%')
    print('% of Outlier in  lower: ',round(df[df[fieldName]<L_outliers][fieldName].count()*100/len(df)), '%')
    
    fig, (ax1,ax2)=plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(13,5))

    #boxplot
    sns.boxplot(x=fieldName,data=df,orient='v',ax=ax1)
    ax1.set_ylabel(fieldName, fontsize=15)
    ax1.set_title('Distribution of '+ fieldName, fontsize=15)
    ax1.tick_params(labelsize=15)

    #distplot
    sns.distplot(df[fieldName])

Observations¶

From diagonal plots we can see

  • avg_credit_limit has 2 major peaks and 1 tail peak
  • total_credit_cards - shows four peaks majorily
  • total_visits_bank - is majorly 3 but 2 minor clusters
  • total_visits_online shows 1 major but 3 minor clusters
  • total_calls_made shows 3 clusters

From bivariate plots we can observe:

  • positive liner relationship with total_visits_online with avg_credit_limit and total_credit_cards
  • total_calls_made shows negative correlation with avg_credit_limit
  • Customer with lower credit limit or less cards make more calls/ bank visits then online, and vice versa

#Finding optimal no. of clusters
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score, adjusted_rand_score
clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(ccdata_z)
    prediction=model.predict(ccdata_z)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(ccdata_z, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / ccdata_z
                           .shape[0])
    if k == 1 :
        sscore= 0;
    else :    
        sscore = silhouette_score(ccdata_z, model.labels_)
    print('cluster :', k , ': silhouette_score :' , sscore)
    resultMap= {'1_Cluster' : 'KMeans', '2_no_of_cluster' : k,
                '3_silhouette_score' : sscore}
    results_df=results_df.append(resultMap,ignore_index=True)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

4. Execute hierarchical clustering (with different linkages) with the help of dendrogram and cophenetic coeff. Analyse clusters formed using boxplot (15 marks)

def clusterbylinkage(results_df,ccdata, ccdata_z,linkageType):
    from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import cophenet, dendrogram, linkage
    from scipy.spatial.distance import pdist  #Pairwise distribution between data points
    from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering 
    
    print('===========LINKAGE:' + linkageType.upper())
    # cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
    # closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering
    if 'GROUP' in ccdata_z.columns:
        ccdata_z= ccdata_z.drop('GROUP',1)
    if 'GROUP' in ccdata.columns:
        ccdata=ccdata.drop('GROUP',1)

    Z = linkage(ccdata_z, metric='euclidean', method='complete')
    c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(ccdata_z))
    
    print ('Cophenet index: ', c)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.title('Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering Dendogram: LINKAGE: '+ linkageType)
    plt.xlabel('sample index')
    plt.ylabel('Distance')
    dendrogram(Z, leaf_rotation=90.,color_threshold = 40, leaf_font_size=8. )
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    for num_clusters in range(2,5):
        #num_clusters=3
        print ('  ===')
        print ('  === LINKAGE:' + linkageType.upper() + ' : num_clusters:', num_clusters)
        # Hint: Use truncate_mode='lastp' attribute in dendrogram function to arrive at dendrogram
        dendrogram(
            Z,
            truncate_mode='lastp',  # show only the last p merged clusters
            p=num_clusters # show only the last p merged clusters
        )
        plt.show()


        model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=num_clusters, affinity='euclidean',  linkage=linkageType)
        prediction=model.fit_predict(ccdata_z)
        # Calculate silhouette_score
        silhouettescore = silhouette_score(ccdata_z, prediction)
        print ('Silhouette_score:', silhouettescore)
        #Append the prediction 
        ccdata_z["GROUP"] = prediction
        ccdata["GROUP"] = prediction
#         print("Groups Assigned : \n")
#         print(ccdata.head())
        ccdataClust = ccdata.groupby(['GROUP'])
        print("Groups Mean : \n")
        print(ccdataClust.mean())

        print("BOX PLOT : \n")
        ccdata_z.boxplot(by='GROUP', layout = (2,4),figsize=(15,10))
        plt.show()
        resultMap= {'1_Cluster' : 'AgglomerativeClustering-'+linkageType, '2_no_of_cluster' : num_clusters,
                '3_silhouette_score' : silhouettescore, '4_cophenet_index': c}
        results_df=results_df.append(resultMap,ignore_index=True)
    
    return results_df;

def clusterbylinkageAndCluster(ccdata, ccdata_z,linkageType, num_clusters):
    from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import cophenet, dendrogram, linkage
    from scipy.spatial.distance import pdist  #Pairwise distribution between data points
    from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering 
    
    print('===========LINKAGE:' + linkageType.upper())
    # cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
    # closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering
    if 'GROUP' in ccdata_z.columns:
        ccdata_z= ccdata_z.drop('GROUP',1)
    if 'GROUP' in ccdata.columns:
        ccdata=ccdata.drop('GROUP',1)
      #num_clusters=3
        print ('  ===')
        print ('  === LINKAGE:' + linkageType.upper() + ' : num_clusters:', num_clusters)
        # Hint: Use truncate_mode='lastp' attribute in dendrogram function to arrive at dendrogram

    model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=num_clusters, affinity='euclidean',  linkage=linkageType)
    prediction=model.fit_predict(ccdata_z)

    silhouettescore = silhouette_score(ccdata_z, prediction)
    print ('Silhouette_score:', silhouettescore)
    #Append the prediction 
    ccdata_z["GROUP"] = prediction
    ccdata["GROUP"] = prediction
#         print("Groups Assigned : \n")
#         print(ccdata.head())
    ccdataClust = ccdata.groupby(['GROUP'])
    print("Groups Mean : \n")
    print(ccdataClust.mean())
    return ccdataClust;

Observation¶

Just looking at avg_credit_limit we can see that the model has identified some low , medium and High Credit limit segments.

Lets understand the differences between these three segments to further determine why they are in separate clusters.

We can see that cluster 3 ( group 2) has a higher number of avg_credit_limit, more total_credit_cards, they make frequent online tranactions and are less likely to visit Bank. There is scope to inform/educate them to increase Online transctions

We can see that cluster 1 ( group 0)has a lower number of avg_credit_limit, less total_credit_cards, they make frequent calls and are less likely to visit Bank.

We can see that cluster 2 ( group 1)make maximuum bank visits and are less likely to do online tranctions

We can draw the conclusion that these are different segments of customers with different support/access needs and therefore there will almost certainly be a difference between how you support to these customers.
